The paper proposes a kernel-based reinforcement learning approach for opportunistic spectrum access, which involves predicting idle slots in spectrum. This falls under the domain of machine learning and optimization, which are covered by several sub-categories in computer science. Specifically, the use of reinforcement learning and function approximation suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are likely categories. Additionally, the paper deals with information theory (cs.IT) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) concepts such as channel access and coexistence with adversarial radios. Finally, the paper proposes a novel budget-constrained sparsification technique, which could be relevant to control and systems engineering (cs.SY).
